Cancer Research UK, while not affiliated with the #nomakeupselfie hashtag, are supporting it

However,
 to begin with the well meaning campaign seemed to have missed a big 
point because nobody appeared to be donating any money in support of 
those that had gone au natural.

Though
 nobody seems to know where the idea came from, the rule seemed to be 
that women post their picture and then nominate other female friends to 
do the same with all posting that the photos were to 'raise awareness of
 cancer' yet with no mention of donating any money.

It didn't take long for people to become a little bemused by the campaign - with many Facebook and Twitter users wondering what the point was if nobody was actually donating cold hard cash.

Luckily Cancer Research UK have now 
cottoned on to the campaign and those posting the selfies or nominating 
others to do so can now text the word BEAT to 70099 TO DONATE £3.

Carolan
 Davidge, director of communications at Cancer Research UK said: 'The 
#nomakeupselfie Twitter trend isn’t something Cancer Research UK started
 – but it’s great to see so many people getting involved to help raise 
awareness of cancer amongst their friends and family.

'If people would like to choose to support our work to beat cancer sooner, they can visit www.cruk.org.'

